        <div class="age" id="age">
            <div class="card">
                <div class="b">The Operator <b>Brief</b>
                </div>
                <p>These are field notes on research-supply vetting, for adults evaluating in a research or operator context. You must be 18 or older to continue.</p>
                <div class="row">
                    <button class="yes" onclick="document.getElementById('age').classList.add('hidden')">I am 18+ · Continue</button>
                    <button class="no" onclick="location.href='https://www.google.com'">Exit</button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="notice">Founder's Field Notes · Supplier Vetting · Part 1 of 2</div>
        <div class="masthead">
            <div class="pub">The Operator <b>Brief</b>
            </div>
            <div class="tag">Supplier vetting, from someone who's done it</div>
        </div>
        <article class="article">
            <div class="eyebrow">Founder's Field Notes</div>
            <h1>After 10 years reviewing Peptide supply chains... the list got suprisingly short.</h1>
            <p class="dek"><b>Before you place your next order </b> &mdash; I&apos;ll provide a supplier that actually passed.</p>
            <img class="article-img" src="https://pub-0a9781e86a6b4f2d9b5bfbe22904ad3c.r2.dev/media/229c955d-9369-446b-8c3b-070268fc0cb2.png" alt="Peptide supplier vetting overview" loading="eager">
            <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            <div class="byline">
                <div class="av"></div>
                <span>By <b>Professor Peps</b> · founder &amp; operator</span>
                <span class="dot">·</span>
                <span>a decade in payments &amp; supply chains</span>
                <span class="dot">·</span>
                <span>5 min read</span>
            </div>
            <p class="lead">For a decade I reviewed businesses, vendors, and supply chains for risk. When I entered the peptide space,&nbsp;<mark>I applied the same process here.&nbsp;</mark> &mdash; Most suppliers look identical on the surface, <b>only a handful held up under deeper scrutiny.&nbsp;</b></p>
            <p>So before I trust a research-peptide supplier, <mark>I run four checks.</mark> If a vendor fails any one of them, <b>I&apos;m</b> <b>out</b> &mdash; <mark>no matter how good the price looks.</mark> Here they are, in the order I run them.<br><br>If you&apos;re reading this, you&apos;re in luck, down below I will review a <b>gem supplier to keep tabs on. Keep reading.</b></p>
            <p></p>
            <img class="article-img" src="https://pub-0a9781e86a6b4f2d9b5bfbe22904ad3c.r2.dev/media/7770cd7a-60a9-4e52-9bd2-1c31bfe67ccd.png" alt="The four-flag vetting framework" loading="lazy">
            <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            <div class="flag-block">
                <div class="flagk">Red flag #1</div>
                <h2>Who actually signed the certificate of analysis?</h2>
                <p>The first thing I look at is who issued the COA. If it came from the supplier itself — their letterhead, their stamp — it's not verification. It's homework graded by the student.</p>
                <p><mark>A real COA comes from an independent third-party lab</mark> — a named one, like Janoshik or Ascend. Anyone can print a document that says "99% pure." Only an outside lab makes it mean anything.</p>
                <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            </div>
            <div class="flag-block">
                <div class="flagk">Red flag #2</div>
                <h2>Is the purity a suspiciously round number?</h2>
                <p>Watch the number itself. If the COA says <strong>98%</strong> or <strong>99%</strong>, I get suspicious. Real chromatography doesn't land on round numbers. It lands on <mark>98.4%</mark>, or 99.1%, or 97.8%.</p>
                <p>A clean, round figure is usually a sign someone typed it — not measured it. <mark>The messy decimal is the one I trust.</mark></p>
                <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            </div>
            <div class="flag-block">
                <div class="flagk">Red flag #3</div>
                <h2>Does the batch number on the vial match the COA?</h2>
                <p>This one catches more vendors than you'd think. The COA is for batch <strong>#23-A488</strong>. The vial in the box says <strong>#23-A491</strong>. Different batch. Which means the certificate you were handed proves nothing about the thing you actually received.</p>
                <p><mark>A COA for a different batch isn't a COA. It's a prop.</mark></p>
                <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            </div>
            <div class="flag-block">
                <div class="flagk">Red flag #4</div>
                <h2>Was this vendor here a year ago — and will they be next year?</h2>
                <p>The last check isn't on the product. It's on the company. A wave of well-known names went dark between 2024 and 2025. Operators who'd built on them were stranded mid-cycle.</p>
                <img class="article-img" src="https://pub-0a9781e86a6b4f2d9b5bfbe22904ad3c.r2.dev/media/836dedc9-230b-4fed-8e45-9894688b1e47.png" alt="Vendor shutdown tracker — names that went dark 2024–2025" loading="lazy">
                <p>Track record is the one thing a new vendor can't fake. If they weren't around twelve months ago, I wait.</p>
                <p class="skip"><a href="#gate">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a></p>
            </div>
            <h2>Notice what isn't on this list: price.</h2>
            <p>Here's the part most people miss. <mark>None of those four checks is about cost.</mark> The cheapest vendor fails most of them — no third-party lab, no batch lineage, gone in a year. So does the overpriced reseller, three middlemen deep, who never touched the product either.</p>
            <p>What the four flags actually test is one thing: <mark>is anyone accountable for what&apos;s in the bottle?</mark> <b>That&apos;s not a price question. It&apos;s a trust question.</b> The vendors the framework approves aren&apos;t the cheapest &mdash; they&apos;re the ones who can answer it.</p>
            <p>The four that passed all share the same things:</p>
            <div class="check">
                <div class="crow y"><span class="ic">✓</span><span><b>A named third-party lab</b> — not a supplier-issued COA</span>
                </div>
                <div class="crow y"><span class="ic">✓</span><span><b>Specific purity numbers</b> — the messy decimal, not the round one</span>
                </div>
                <div class="crow y"><span class="ic">✓</span><span><b>Batch lineage that matches</b> — vial to COA, every time</span>
                </div>
                <div class="crow y"><span class="ic">✓</span><span><b>How recent was the COA issued?</b> &mdash; The recommended supplier I will review updates very often.&nbsp;</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="gate" id="gate">
                <h2>Start with the one, <i><b>I reviewed secretly</b></i>, who passed the review.</h2>
                <p>When people ask me where to actually start, I point them to one supplier that clears all four — third-party lab, specific numbers, matching batch, a real track record. Confirm the context and I'll send you there.</p>
                <label class="chk">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="q" onchange="var b=document.getElementById('go');b.classList.toggle('locked',!this.checked)">
                    <span>I'm 18 or older, I'm evaluating in a research / operator context, and I understand nothing here is medical, legal, financial, or business advice.</span>
                </label>
                <a href="{{ route('outbound.track', 'lp-10-years') }}" id="go" class="cta locked" rel="nofollow" onclick="return document.getElementById('q').checked">Take me to the recommended supplier →</a>
                <div class="cta-sub" style="color:#9fb0a7;margin-top:10px">Opens the supplier I recommend · biolinxlabs.com</div>
            </div>
            <div class="refs">
                <div class="refs-h">Sources &amp; methodology · the receipts behind the list</div>
                <details class="drop">
                    <summary>How a supplier actually gets vetted — the 5-step process</summary>
                    <div class="db">
                        <p>"Vetted" isn't a vibe. It's a process you can run on anyone:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><b>Initial outreach.</b> Ask for the product list, minimum order, lead time, and three recent COAs from <em>different</em> batches. How fast and how cleanly they answer tells you most of it.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Sample order.</b> Buy two or three at sample quantity. Watch the packaging, the cold-chain handling, the communication.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Third-party verification.</b> Send every vial to an independent lab — Janoshik, Ascend — and confirm identity, purity, and endotoxin yourself. Don't take the supplier's word.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Pilot run.</b> Order 50–100 and track reorder rate and feedback over 30 days. Real-world consistency, not one good batch.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Lock terms.</b> Net-30, batch consistency, backup stock — the boring paperwork that means they'll still be here next year.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <div class="src">Process compiled from the operator playbook this brief works from.</div>
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="drop">
                    <summary>The vendor databases I cross-check</summary>
                    <div class="db">
                        <p>I don't run this on instinct. Before I trust a name, I check it against the same independent sources the community uses:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><b>Finnrick Analytics.</b> Independent vendor-testing database — thousands of lab-tested samples, purity ratings, fill-accuracy analysis, vendor score tracking.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>The Peptide Catalog.</b> Vendor reviews, a shutdown tracker, and market-wide price comparisons.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Outliyr — best peptide companies.</b> Ranked vendor lists with a published scoring methodology.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>r/Peptides.</b> Uncensored community feedback — search a vendor's name for unfiltered, real-world experiences.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>r/Tirzepatide.</b> GLP-1-specific batch-consistency and reliability reports.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Janoshik &amp; Aminos Analytics.</b> The third-party labs vials actually get sent to — HPLC, mass-spec, identity verification.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <div class="src">Listed so you can check my work — not as referrals. The only door I'll point you through is the one below.</div>
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="drop">
                    <summary>The international manufacturers I keep tabs on</summary>
                    <div class="db">
                        <p>Knowing the raw-material layer matters — it's where purity and consistency are won or lost. The bulk manufacturers I track:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><b>Pengting Peptide.</b> GMP-certified bulk raw materials.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>PurePeptide Labs.</b> B2B OEM and custom synthesis.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Global Peptide Mfg.</b> Bulk supply and OEM custom synthesis.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Nanjing Peptide Biotech.</b> Licensed research-peptide source, operating since 2013.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Chinese Peptide Company.</b> Bulk and wholesale R&amp;D supply.
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Suzhou Peptides.</b> Bulk exporter to the US, EU, Canada, and AU.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        <div class="src">Named for context only — no links, no endorsements. Knowing the layer is the point; the supplier I trust is below.</div>
                    </div>
                </details>
            </div>
